1ï¸âƒ£ What is an ECS Task (simple)

An ECS Task is:

A running instance of a Task Definition.

Think of it like:

Task Definition = blueprint
Task            = running container(s)

2ï¸âƒ£ What we define in a Task Definition (MOST IMPORTANT)

A Task Definition tells ECS how to run your container(s).

ğŸ”¹ 1. Docker image
Which image to run


Example:

Rails API image

Elixir notification image

ğŸ”¹ 2. CPU & Memory
How much compute this task needs


Example:

Rails: more memory

Elixir consumer: more CPU

ğŸ”¹ 3. Container port mapping
Which ports are exposed


Example:

Rails â†’ 3000

Elixir â†’ often none (background worker)

ğŸ”¹ 4. Environment variables
Runtime configuration


Examples:

DATABASE_URL

SECRET_KEY_BASE

KAFKA_BROKERS

ğŸ”¥ Very important:

Never hardcode secrets â€” use env vars / AWS Secrets Manager

ğŸ”¹ 5. Command / entrypoint
What starts inside the container


Examples:

bundle exec puma

mix run --no-halt

ğŸ”¹ 6. IAM role (very important)
What AWS services this task can access


Examples:

S3

SQS

CloudWatch logs

ğŸ”¥ Interview line:

â€œECS tasks use IAM roles instead of access keys.â€

ğŸ”¹ 7. Logging configuration
Where logs go


Usually:

CloudWatch Logs

ğŸ”¹ 8. Networking mode
How container gets network access


Most common:

awsvpc (each task gets its own IP)

ğŸ”¹ 9. Health checks
How ECS knows container is healthy


Example:

HTTP /health

Process running

